In Java, you can use the `+` operator to add two numbers together. For example:
```
int a = 5;
int b = 3;
int sum = a + b;
System.out.println(sum); // prints 8
```
If you have two digit variables, you can simply add them together as shown above. However, if you want to handle the case where one of the digits is a string or a character, you will need to use the `+` operator with caution. For example:
```
int a = 5;
char b = 'a';
String sum = String.valueOf(a) + b;
System.out.println(sum); // prints "5a"
```
In this case, we are concatenating the string representation of `a` with the character `b`. Note that we need to use the `String.valueOf()` method to convert the integer `a` to a string first before we can concatenate it with `b`.
